b:["$","div",null,{"className":"prose","children":[["$","h2",null,{"children":"Who Should Choose Which?"}],["$","p",null,{"children":"The ideal user for each platform differs considerably. Docsumo is best suited for lending companies, insurance, accounting firms, making it a strong choice if you fall into any of these categories. Make (Integromat), meanwhile, shines for power users, agencies, complex automations, which means it may be the better pick if your needs align with those use cases.\n\nFounded in 2019, Docsumo describes itself as \"AI-powered document data extraction for business automation.\" Make (Integromat), established in 2012, positions itself as \"Visual platform for designing, building, and automating complex workflows.\" With 7 years between them, Make (Integromat) brings the maturity and proven track record of a veteran platform, while Docsumo offers the fresh perspective and modern architecture of a newer entrant."}]]}]
c:["$","div",null,{"className":"verdict-box","children":[["$","h2",null,{"children":"Our Verdict"}],["$","p",null,{"children":"After analyzing all the data, **Make (Integromat)** comes out slightly ahead in this comparison, thanks to higher user ratings (9.0 vs 7.0), availability of a free plan. However, this does not mean Docsumo is a poor choice — far from it. Docsumo excels in its own right, particularly for lending companies and insurance.\n\nOur recommendation: if you value superior visual workflow builder, go with Make (Integromat). If high extraction accuracy out of the box matters more to you, Docsumo is the way to go. Either way, both are solid platforms that have earned their place in the market."}]]}]
